cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CC, cs.GT. 

The paper deals with a geometric version of the generalized red-blue set cover problem, where the elements are points in the plane and sets are defined by lines. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the study of parameterized complexity, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The use of families of sets and the investigation of the existence of polynomial kernels suggest that the paper could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
